<span id="freeTextContainer12947367389454011092">Joseph, aka Tiny, never knew his mother. According to his father, she left when he was born. Right after his thirteenth birthday, his father was diagnosed with the beginning stages of lung cancer and decided to continually stay high rather than deal with the disease. The disability check was just enough to pay for their trailer and utilities but not really enough for groceries. And Tiny was ALWAYS hungry. Not only that but where school was suppose to be a reprieve for the harshness of his realit</span>
  <span id="freeText12947367389454011092" style="display:none">Joseph, aka Tiny, never knew his mother. According to his father, she left when he was born. Right after his thirteenth birthday, his father was diagnosed with the beginning stages of lung cancer and decided to continually stay high rather than deal with the disease. The disability check was just enough to pay for their trailer and utilities but not really enough for groceries. And Tiny was ALWAYS hungry. Not only that but where school was suppose to be a reprieve for the harshness of his reality, it only made things worse. The teachers didn't like him because of his father's reputation with the drugs. Add Tiny's angry, rebellious nature and you had a combination for disaster. Who could blame him? He had a father who was busy with drugs and whoring around while the son was continually in fights to defend himself and his old man against the dealers wanting their money or retribution often times leaving Tiny either in Juvie or the hospital. When his father pulled up outside a ratty looking trailer telling him he needed to get his clothes and go inside where his mother was, of course Tiny was angry. Before he could barely make it to the door, his father had pulled away leaving him to face a young girl out in the yard.<br />Eleven year old Madison had her own demons she was living with. Her mother was a drug addict and prostitute. The shame of that alone was enough to humiliate anyone, but Madison looked like she was at least fifteen so the same crude clientele her mother had would often humiliate and instill fear in her.<br />I just finished this book and I have to admit it, my hands are shaking and my stomach feels like there's a whirlwind of butterflies set loose. This is such a dark, twisted romance where the two lead characters can't seem to get a break!! I've smiled at a few places in through the story that warmed my heart, shed tears where I felt it was broken and completely had the shakes over the intensity of what is being told. This is the first book by Angel Rose I've read and I'm not disappointed in the least. This one has grabbed hold and hadn't let go. There's a major cliffhanger but I'm immediately on my way to start the next one to find out what happens.<br /></span>
